vemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-1.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-1.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Allopatric speciation in trees (2)" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="671" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-2.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Allopatric speciation in trees (3)" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="727" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Allopatric-speciation-in-trees-3.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>The geographical barrier of a mountain range can lead to allopatric speciation in trees</b></i></p><h4 id="sympatric-speciation">Sympatric speciation</h4><ul><li><p>Sympatric speciation takes place with <b>no geographical barrier</b></p></li><li><p>Isolation instead occurs when random changes in the <b>alleles</b> and therefore <b>phenotypes</b> of some individuals in a population <b>prevent</b> them from successfully <b>breeding</b> with other individuals in the population</p></li><li><p>Examples of phenotype changes that can lead to isolation include</p><ul><li><p><b>Seasonal</b> <b>changes</b></p><ul><li><p>Some individuals in a population may develop different <b>mating</b> or <b>flowering</b> seasons to the rest of the population, i.e their <b>reproductive timings</b> no longer match up</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>Mechanical changes</b></p><ul><li><p>Some individuals in a population may develop changes in their <b>genitalia</b> that prevent them from <b>mating</b> successfully with individuals of the opposite sex, i.e. their <b>reproductive body parts</b> no longer match up</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>Behavioural changes</b></p><ul><li><p>Some individuals in a population may develop changes in their <b>courtship behaviours</b> meaning they can no longer <b>attract</b> individuals of the opposite sex for <b>mating,</b> i.e. their methods of attracting a mate are no longer effective</p></li></ul></li></ul></li><li><p>The populations may still <b>live in the same habitat</b> but they are isolated from each other in the sense that they <b>do not interbreed</b></p></li><li><p>The lack of gene flow between the two populations means that allele frequencies in the gene pools of the two populations may change in different ways</p></li><li><p>Changing allele frequencies will lead to changes in the phenotypes of the two populations</p></li><li><p>If enough allele frequency differences arise between the two populations then they will eventually no longer be able to <b>breed with each other</b> and <b>produce fertile offspring</b>, and can be said to be <b>separate species</b></p></li></ul><h4 id="e-g-sympatric-speciation-in-fruit-flies">E.g. sympatric speciation in fruit flies</h4><ul><li><p>A population of fruit flies exists in a laboratory</p></li><li><p>A random allele change resulting from mutation <b>divides the species</b> into <b>two populations</b></p><ul><li><p>The allele changes leads to a change in phenotype, e.g. food preference</p></li></ul></li><li><p>The difference in phenotype prevents the two populations from <b>interbreeding</b> so there is <b>no gene flow</b> between them</p></li><li><p>Different alleles are therefore <b>passed on</b> in each population</p><ul><li><p>This could be due to difference in selection pressure, e.g. certain enzymes are advantageous for the digestion of different foods or due to random passing on of different alleles</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Different alleles become <b>more frequent</b> in each population</p></li><li><p>Over time the divided populations <b>form two distinct species</b> that can no longer interbreed to produce fertile offspring</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Reproductive separation" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="798" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Reproductive-separation.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/04/Reproductive-separation.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Isolation mechanisms other than geographical isolation can also lead to speciation</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="exam-tip"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M9 21c0 .5.4 1 1 1h4c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-1H9v1zm3-19C8.1 2 5 5.1 5 9c0 2.4 1.2 4.5 3 5.7V17c0 .5.4 1 1 1h6c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-2.3c1.8-1.3 3-3.4 3-5.7 0-3.9-3.1-7-7-7z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Examiner Tips and Tricks</h4></header><p>Note that you need to be able to apply the principles of <b>natural selection</b> to the process of speciation; the difference here is that natural selection will be acting differently on <b>two</b> isolated populations;</p><ol start="1"><li><p>Variation is present</p></li><li><p>Selection pressures act on a population</p><ul><li><p>These may be different between two isolated populations</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Advantageous alleles provide some individuals with increase survival and reproduction chances</p><ul><li><p>Advantageous alleles may be different between two isolated populations</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Advantageous alleles are passed on</p></li><li><p>Allele frequencies change</p><ul><li><p>Different advantageous alleles will accumulate in the two isolated populations until they become so different that they can no longer interbreed</p></li></ul></li></ol></div></div></div></div>